The formal property is that a reward function must not permit unbounded cumulative returns from any trajectory consisting solely of no-op (null) actions. Mathematically, for any state s, the infinite-horizon discounted return ∑ᵢ γⁱ r(s, no-op) must be finite. This prevents reward hacking where an agent exploits looping in a state without accomplishing its intended objective. The property ensures the reward function incentivizes actual progress rather than static state-dwelling. This is sometimes called **reward boundedness** or **non-exploitability by null policies**. Without this constraint, agents could achieve arbitrarily high scores by repeatedly executing null actions, rendering the reward signal meaningless for task specification.